<h1>@HI{{uchi ni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> @Vnai{{}} <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> @Vte{{}} @HI{{iru}} <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> @Ai{{}} <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> @Ana{{}} <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> <em>quantifier(period)</em> <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong> expresses the general time in which a state or action occurs.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{consider}}eteiru<strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}@KJ{{part}}kara naku natta.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While thinking about it, I got lost.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rain}}ga@KJ{{descend}}ranai <strong>uchi ni</strong>@KT{{tenisu}}wo shite kimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll go and play tennis (and come back) before it rains.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{warm}}kai<strong>uchi ni</strong>@KJ{{drink}}de kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please drink it while it is warm.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rest}}mino<strong>uchi ni</strong>yoku@KJ{{sleep}}teokimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll sleep a lot during the summer holiday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The expression before <strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong> is always non-past even if the sentence itself is in the past.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{uchi ni}}</strong> cannot be used where the noun used is an event such as a class.
</p>

